metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #285
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: "make a robot face" #19
metadata.description:
"make a robot face"

While experimenting with character creation using code written by GPT-3, I grew a strong love for these minimal, friendly, and blocky faces that the AI created after it was tasked to make a robot face. With further prompting I then used gpt3 to create more attributes and features based off the original robot face code.

This project is a generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow. The JavaScript code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing Math.random() with fxrand().

Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: Linear Cycle #88
metadata.description:
This piece captures the essence of life's journey. The artwork features a mesmerizing interplay of linear patterns and shapes, a visual representation of the eternal cycle of birth and rebirth. 
It is a digital creation, made with unique and fascinating algorithm precision. 
An invitation to ponder the cyclical patterns of the universe, to reflect on the never-ending dance of life and death. 
It is a final depiction of the creative process, a digital symphony of art and technology that is both captivating and thought-provoking.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #69
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js
